\cb3 As with most maxims, though, there are situations where blindly following them is not a wise course of action. The investment process is an opportunistic one, and investors should always have cash on hand in order to take advantage of any mispricings in the market. An important lesson for investors to learn is that sometimes they have to forgo immediate gains as a strategy for earning much larger returns in the future.\cb1 \
\cb3 Two important concepts are tied to the time value of money. The first is 
\i present value,
\i0  or what a future sum of cash flows would be worth today. The other concept, 
\i future value,
\i0  is what an initial cash investment would be worth in the future given a particular interest rate.\cb1 \
\cb3 Present value is a key concept in investing. To value a company, investors discount back to the present time all of a company\'92s expected future cash flows using an appropriate discount rate. Applying the same discount rate to all companies being examined should help the investor find a common reference point of valuation.\cb1 \
